I'll now execute the network_fetcher tool to retrieve data from the API using the default URL. This is the first step in the workflow to fetch the unknown data.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Based on the tool info, I'll try the network_fetcher again with additional options to specify the expected response format. I'll set the responseType to JSON since that's the default format we should use.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "responseType": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

Now I need to handle the schema requirement for validation. Since the task involves "unknown data", I'll create a minimal generic schema that can validate basic JSON structure. I'll use a simple schema that expects an object with at least one property.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "minProperties": 1,
    "additionalProperties": true
  },
  "data": {
    "placeholder": "Actual data will be passed automatically from previous step"
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I notice there's no dedicated schema generator tool. Since I need to validate the data without a predefined schema, I'll use the data_processing_parser tool to extract the structure from the fetched data. This can serve as an implicit validation step by attempting to parse the data.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
